In article <1993Apr3.141738.2260@infodev.cam.ac.uk> Mark.Lomas@cl.cam.ac.uk writes:
>I recently posted a message giving an example of a scheme for registering
>documents without revealing them.  Several people have since suggested that
>I got the idea from recent work at Bellcore and should therefore have cited
>them.
>
>However Li Gong at SRI has just reminded me that I first described the
>scheme to him before he moved to the USA in May 1990.  I had envisaged an
>on-line repository for these signatures that I called an Electronic Notary.
>
>A similar scheme also appears in a anonymous French submission to ISO later
>that year so I know that others discovered it independently of me.
>
>Maybe somebody should start one of these services so that people can register
>ideas such as this.  :-)
>
>	Mark


Well, I'm surprised that nobody pointed out, that this system is quite
old ; Newton, Laplas (spelling) and many others used so called "anagrams"
for the establishing priority in science.
